    <name>
				<text>14.3.2.4 Find volume of line around y-axis</text>
		</name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p class="HELM_exercise">Exercise</p>
<p>The curve \(y={@f@}\) for \({@low@}&lt;x&lt;{@upp@}\) is rotated about the \(y\)-axis. Find the volume of the solid formed.</p>
<p>\(\quad V =\) [[input:ans3]] [[validation:ans3]] [[feedback:prt3]]</p>]]></text>
		</questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<h4 class="HELM_solution">Solution</h4>
<p>Using the latest Key Point, the required integral is \[\int_{@ta2dn@}^{@ta2up@} {@ta2int@} \,\mathrm{d}y,\] since \(c={@ta2dn@}\) and \(d={@ta2up@}\).Since&nbsp;<span style="font-size: 0.9375rem;">at \(x={@low@}\) we have \(y={@ta2dn@}\) and&nbsp;at \(x={@upp@}\) we have \(y={@ta2ip@}\)</span></p>
<p>We have \(y={@f@}\), so \(x^2={@x_sq@}\) and the volume becomes \[\begin{align} \int_{@ta2dn@}^{@ta2up@} {@pi*x_sq@} \,\mathrm{d}y &amp;= \pi \left[ {@integrate(x_sq,y)@} \right]_{@ta2dn@}^{@ta2up@} \\ &amp;=\pi \left[ {@subst(y=ta2up,integrate(x_sq,y))@}-{@subst(y=ta2dn,integrate(x_sq,y))@}
    \right] \\ &amp;= {@ta3@} \end{align}\]</p>]]></text>
		</generalfeedback>
